The infinite symmetric product SP^infty(S^n) is a nice model for 
K(Z,n), and then there is M.C.McCord's generalization that gives 
K(pi,n).  See the beginning of the Math Review that I have copied 
below.  These are all obviously commutative monoids, and it seems to 
me that naturality in the pi variable should give the inverse when 
applied to -: pi --> pi.

Nick Kuhn

MR0251719 (40 #4946)
McCord, M. C.
Classifying spaces and infinite symmetric products.
Trans. Amer. Math. Soc. 146 1969 273--298.

If $X$ is a topological space with base point * and $G$ is a 
topological monoid with unit $e$, let $B(G,X)$ be the reduced monoid 
of singular 0-chains of $X$ with coefficients in $G$, i.e., the set of 
all functions $(X,\ast)\rightarrow(G,e)$ with finite support. The 
author shows that $B(G,X)$, suitably topologized, has very remarkable 
properties, and that it generalizes several basic constructions of 
algebraic topology. For example, $B({\bf Z}^+,X)=\text{SP}^\infty X=$ 
infinite symmetric product of $X$, $B(G,S^n)=K(G,n)=$ 
Eilenberg-MacLane complex if $G$ is a discrete abelian group, 
$B(G,[0,1])\rightarrow B(G,S^1)$ is a numerable universal $G$-bundle 
if $G$ is a topological group such that $\ast\rightarrow G$ is a 
cofibration.

