Here is a golden oldy.  Jim, this may be from when you were a graduate
student,  before my time anyway, so it might be what you remembering.
In any case, I'll take this as a teaching or preaching opportunity.

There is a beautiful and long forgotten construction of
K(\pi,n) as a simplicial abelian group that makes the
representability of cohomology utterly transparent.
It is due to Adrien Douady and can be found in expos\'e 9
of Volume I of the 1958/59 S\'eminaire Henri Cartan,
``Invariant de Hopf et operations cohomologique secondaires''.

Briefly, the abelian group of q-simplices of K(\pi,n) is just
the normalized simplicial n-cochains with coefficients in \pi
of the standard simplicial q-simplex \Delta_q.  Since the
\Delta_q are the objects of a cosimplicial set, it is
immediate that this definition prescribes a simplicial
abelian group.

Starting from this definition, Douady proves directly that
K(\pi,n) represents cohomology, and it follows as a corollary
that it has the right homotopy groups to be a K(\pi,n).

----------------------------------------------------------------------

