I was working in this area in 1960-61 for my thesis on function spaces, 
determining k^Y where k is a cohomology operation and Y is a space, so I 
hope this background will be helpful.

Dold had a preprint giving a rather combinatorial description of the 
functor say Phi from  chain complexes to simplicial abelian groups, and 
this is used by others, such as David Epstein, but, as Michael Barratt 
put it to me, Kan cast a huge light on this area by describing Phi(A) in 
dimension n as the chain maps from the normalised chains of the 
n-simplex to A; this can be thought of, analogously to what Peter says,  
as the cochains of the n-simplex with coefficients in the chain complex 
A, and this was the view I took in my thesis published in part as

 3. ``Cohomology with chains as coefficients'', {\em Proc.London Math. 
Soc.}  (3) 14 (1964), 545-565.

Actually while taking the view of replacing the \pi in K(\pi,n) by a 
chain complex I discovered the Dold-Kan theorem - too late! The reason 
for doing this replacement was that if Y was a simplicial set then 
K(\pi,n)^Y could be considered as K(C^*(Y, \pi),n),  with the right 
conventions. This involves the various exponential laws in chain 
complexes and simplicial abelian groups. And Andre Joyal has recently 
looked again at the other tensor product on chains obtained from the 
equivalence with simplicial abelian groups, and the natural tensor 
there, as those who were at CT2010 will know.

Another facet of the Dold-Kan  equivalence is the paper of A.L. Blakers

Blakers, A. Some relations between homology and homotopy groups. {Ann. 
of Math. (2)} \textbf{49} (1948) 428--461.

who defines a `group system', now called a crossed complex, and using 
relative homotopy groups defines for a filtered space (with X_0 a 
singleton) what we call the fundamental crossed complex. This paper uses 
the homotopy addition lemma for a simplex. I heard from Michael Barratt 
in the late 1950s that it was suddenly realised in Princeton that this 
had not been proved: so who to ask to prove it? The answer was shown in
Hu, S.-T. {The homotopy addition theorem}.Ann. of Math. (2) {58} (1953) 
108--122.

Blakers also assigns  to a reduced crossed complex, C, a simplicial set 
which nowadays we would call the nerve NC of C, and which in dimension n 
can also be seen as the cochains of the n-simplex with coefficients in 
the (partially nonabelian) crossed complex C. The functor N gives an 
equivalence between crossed complexes and simplicial T-complexes 
(Ashley's theorem, 1978, in his PhD).

Ronnie Brown
